@@dSepulchur Pasture@@N

  Where @@yMidgaard's@@N promises to the dead are tested. South of the city,
beyond the ninth milestone, low fields and burial mounds from older
clans once formed simple working ground. Shepherd-priests called
@@dBell Cairn Walkers@@N rang a single bell at dusk to guide the lost --
not a summons, but a promise that someone was still listening.

  Then Midgaard grew. Road dead were routed to the acre. Names were
copied from signet rings and contracts. Effects were cataloged for
return or forfeiture. Graves were marked by category if not by
certainty. What began as mercy became a civic machine. The old field
became @@dSepulchur Pasture@@N, where the promise to remember met the
need to account.

  During the @@rAsh-and-Iron Decades@@N -- when Cinderteeth eruptions,
western route collapse, and northern raids overwhelmed every district
-- a burial tariff was imposed. The @@yTithe of Last Burdens@@N funded
guards, carts, salt, and bells. Families who could pay bought
sanctified plots. Those who could not were entered as @@d"deferred
names"@@N and interred in common furrows pending claim.

  Over time, a quiet industry formed around grief: clerks charging for
corrections, carriers misplacing evidence, wardens delaying release
of remains, brokers trading rumor of inheritance marks. The field no
longer only held the dead. It held debt.

  When the @@lViolet Compact's@@N containment doctrine spread beyond the
inner reliquary corridors, certain remains -- plague-touched, curse-
ridden, or arcane-active -- were forbidden from immediate burial.
Holding pens, wardwire trenches, and witness lantern circles were
added. The dead were detained in legal limbo.

  Then the @@rgravebell answered itself@@N. After three mass interments from
frontier skirmishes, the night watch heard the bell ring twice for
every pull: once from the tower, once from somewhere beneath the
furrows. Clerks found ledger irregularities -- names recorded but no
bodies found, bodies interred but no names retained, claim tokens
duplicated across unrelated dead. The phrase "deferred name" stopped
meaning paperwork and started meaning unrest.

  Sister Calvea of the Ninth Peal argued that repeated bell tolls
trapped grief in ritual loops. Her unauthorized night rites soothed
disturbances briefly before Compact adjudicators banned them. The
@@dBell-Eaten Steward@@N -- once a human superintendent -- now walks
the core crypt carrying keys and tariff seals fused into bone.

  Children in nearby wards still repeat at dusk: @@e"Pay the living,
name the dead, and do not let the bell count twice."@@N
